{
    "name": "Crawling Slurry",
    "type": "creature",
    "sections": [
        {
            "name": "Crawling Slurry",
            "type": "section",
            "sections": [
                {
                    "name": "Accidental Oozes",
                    "type": "section",
                    "text": "Crawling slurries are almost always by-products of toxic waste or alchemical runoff into areas with a high concentration of acid, magic, or both. The first quickening pulses of animation in acid-pitted flesh are easy enough to end with counteracting chemicals or even isolation and starvation, but most crawling slurries are left to fester for a long time and become as large as a person. Left untended in a vat of nutritive acids and organic matter, a crawling slurry might become truly immense, but the power such a slithering horror holds is beyond comprehension.",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Pathfinder #174: Shadows of the Ancients",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Pathfinder #174: Shadows of the Ancients pg. 82",
                                "alt": "Pathfinder #174: Shadows of the Ancients pg. 82",
                                "game-obj": "Sources",
                                "aonid": 115
                            },
                            "page": 82
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "additional_lore",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Additional Lore",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Additional Lore",
                        "image": "Sidebar_2_AdditionalLore.png"
                    }
                }
            ],
            "text": "Acid damage can scar stone and reduce flesh to pitted chunks, but some organic compounds are resistant to acid and respond by combining into a mass of roiling, living slurry. These scarred clumps hunger to consume anything they can sense. They move with quick, darting contractions that surprise those used to facing slow-moving oozes.",
            "sources": [
                {
                    "type": "source",
                    "name": "Pathfinder #174: Shadows of the Ancients",
                    "link": {
                        "type": "link",
                        "name": "Pathfinder #174: Shadows of the Ancients pg. 82",
                        "alt": "Pathfinder #174: Shadows of the Ancients pg. 82",
                        "game-obj": "Sources",
                        "aonid": 115
                    },
                    "page": 82
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "name": "Ooze",
            "type": "section",
            "sections": [
                {
                    "name": "Amoebas Large and Small",
                    "type": "section",
                    "text": "Giant amoebas and amoeba swarms are usually found near each other, as the two oozes are part of the same life cycle. When a giant amoeba grows large enough, it can spontaneously split apart into two separate amoeba swarms, and when an amoeba swarm feeds enough, its individual components can fuse together into a single creature.",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Bestiary",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "alt": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "game-obj": "Sources",
                                "aonid": 2
                            },
                            "page": 254
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "related_creatures",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Related Creatures",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Related Creatures",
                        "image": "Sidebar_4_RelatedCreatures.png"
                    },
                    "links": [
                        {
                            "type": "link",
                            "name": "Giant amoebas",
                            "alt": "Giant amoebas",
                            "game-obj": "Monsters",
                            "aonid": 751
                        },
                        {
                            "type": "link",
                            "name": "amoeba swarms",
                            "alt": "amoeba swarms",
                            "game-obj": "Monsters",
                            "aonid": 750
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "name": "Oozing Acid",
                    "type": "section",
                    "text": "Many oozes have acidic attacks that can quickly degrade flesh, wood, and even stronger materials. Some believe that oozes are the result of alchemical or magical experimentation run amok, while others postulate that they simply emerged from the natural processes of evolution.",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Bestiary",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "alt": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "game-obj": "Sources",
                                "aonid": 2
                            },
                            "page": 254
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "additional_lore",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Additional Lore",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Additional Lore",
                        "image": "Sidebar_2_AdditionalLore.png"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "name": "Other Oozes",
                    "type": "section",
                    "text": "Many varieties of these nearly mindless predators exist in the world. Some are mere variants, with different colored puddings, jellies, and oozes with little to differentiate them from those presented here other than their habitat. Others are more specialized, or even dangerously intelligent. The shoggoth is one such example, but another variety of deadly and powerful ooze is the thankfully rare blight, a creature composed of protoplasm and eyes that curses entire regions with its presence.",
                    "sources": [
                        {
                            "type": "source",
                            "name": "Bestiary",
                            "link": {
                                "type": "link",
                                "name": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "alt": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                                "game-obj": "Sources",
                                "aonid": 2
                            },
                            "page": 254
                        }
                    ],
                    "subtype": "sidebar",
                    "sidebar_type": "related_creatures",
                    "sidebar_heading": "Related Creatures",
                    "image": {
                        "type": "image",
                        "name": "Related Creatures",
                        "image": "Sidebar_4_RelatedCreatures.png"
                    },
                    "links": [
                        {
                            "type": "link",
                            "name": "shoggoth",
                            "alt": "shoggoth",
                            "game-obj": "Monsters",
                            "aonid": 368
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ],
            "text": "Slimes, molds, and other oozes can be found in dank dungeons and shadowed forests. While not necessarily evil, some grow to enormous sizes and have insatiable appetites.",
            "sources": [
                {
                    "type": "source",
                    "name": "Bestiary",
                    "link": {
                        "type": "link",
                        "name": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                        "alt": "Bestiary pg. 254",
                        "game-obj": "Sources",
                        "aonid": 2
                    },
                    "page": 254
                }
            ]
        }
    ],
